Was sharing this w/ @Griff (💜,💜) and he suggested dropping it here on params. 
A number of our most popular proposals change tribute percentages over time (like those by @Griff (💜,💜), @Tamarandom, @Juankbell, @divine_comedian, @liviade, @iviangita, @Zeptimus, to name a few). 
It got me asking, if investors knew we were doing this, why wouldn't they just wait for future tranches, with lower tributes? 

And then it hit me: one reason might is simply the willingness to invest with greater impact. So, what if we embraced this by very intentionally adopting a curve that clearly distinguished and celebrated the early tranches with deeper tributes and more impact on the mission?

For example, let's say we set the first entry tribute at 50% (example only; we could go lower/higher) for a 3-week period. These obvious impact investors could receive a special POAP to celebrate their deep commitment to the mission. Next tranche might be 25% and a different POAP, etc. It might use some fairly low minimum size of investment to qualify, but the key here is that it's not the size of the investment -- it's the commitment to a public goods mission (the "donative quality" of the investment) that is the distinction. 

This draws on the techniques of time-based "price skimming" but rather than optimizing for profit, this "impact skimming" optimizes for mission. We'd be crafting a mechanism that allows different orientations toward impact to play on the same token, using time as the way to segment.  It's engineering a bonding curve that seamlessly and automatically moves from impact investing to regular investing over time.
